Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

BAIL HEARING - 
Defendant in custody and appearing by video from the Manitowoc County Jail.  The State informs the Court that the defendant will be charged with the crimes of possess methamphetamine and possess Fentanyl.  The matters are continued for initial appearance on 10-03-22 at 1:30 p.m. Br. 1.  Bail is set at $500.00 cash with the conditions that she have no contact with Matthew Vertz, Joshua Roepke and Brandon Tompkins.   The Court will allow a one time contact with the residence, with the aid of law enforcement, after the 72 hour no contact provision has expired to obtain personal belongings.  Defendant is to have no contact with any known drug users or dealer and must maintain absolute sobriety.  Bail not furnished and defendant is remanded into custody. 
Commitment for failure to furnish bail issued.  Copy filed.
